{"/service/ndnp/nvln/batch_nvln_aurora_ver02/data/sn86076142/00415626940/1908030301/0225.xml":{"full_text":"TOXOPAH DAILY I'.ONAXZA, TOXOl'AH. NEVADA, MAIICH 3, JOH.\nTONOPAH DAILY BONANZA\nPublished Every Morning, Mommy Excepted, at Tonopah, Kevada\nsar. W. BOOTH,\nEditor and Proprietor\nI. S. DAVELEft,\nManager\nMember of Associated Presn\nTERMS OF SUBSCRIPTION\nyear 111.09 I Three months\nMine moiuliB 10.00 I One mouth\nXx months .75 One week\nSubscriptions by mail must be paid for in advance.\n$.50\nl.!S\n.11\nTEN DOLLARS REWARD\nA reward of $10 will ba paid for in\nformation that will lesil to the arn-st\nand convirtion of parties stealing The\nBonanza from premises of subscriber.\nTO SUBSCRIBERS\nParties who do not receive their\nDapere. or who have any cause of com\nplaint, will oblige by notifying this\noffice.\nEntered at the Fostoffice in Tonopdh ai second class matter.\nEDITORIAL COMMENT\nMEANS MUCH FOR THE COUNTRY.\nThe resumption of work in the mines of Butte and Anaconda can\nliresage only one thing, and that is the return, on the double quick, of\nprosperity's march. The Associated Press dispatches, which carried the\niiood news, stated that there would be a return to work of 12,000 men.\n'The papers of Butte and Salt Lake state there will be not less thau\n10.000 men go to work.\nThis is not all of the story; it is but thi beginning. The men of\nButie and Anaconda will form but a small proportion of those who will\nve affected by the resumption of work in the mines and the Washoe\n.smelter. The increase of the production of copper means that the red\n:;etal is again in demand, and there are thousands and thousands of\nsnpn engaged in the work where it is used. It means that there will be\nresumption of work in other copper mines, that it will be a good thing\ntor the mines of this State. The price of the metal is bound to in\ncrease and that will warrant a still greater production. There will be n\nSi-eater demand for the silicious ores of this State, there will be more\nmines working. It will be good for the mines of Ely and the smelters;\nit will be good for the mines of Tonopah and ail the producing properties\nof the State.\nThere is another smelter to be opened up on the first of April at Mc\n\"Oill, Nevada. It has just been completed at a cost of 18,000,000, and\n'it ill give employment to many men. The news from Angels Camp in\n(.alitornin is to the effect that all the mines there are again working after\n'having been closed down for a number of months.\nAll .these facts point the return of prosperity, and it looks as if\n\"President Roosevelt had beaten down the financial powers who were re\nsponsible for the panic, and who had threatened to bring about another\nif the big stick were not suspended. The railroads have apparently\ncalled off their threat to retrench to the point of hardship among their\nemployes in order to force the President to let go in his fight against\nthe corporations. Men have been out back to work on the roads and in\nthe shops, and this fait accounts in a great mesure for the demand for\ncopper and the opening of the copper mines. When prosperity begins its\nmarch everybody and every industry joins the procession and the way\nnow seems clear for the march.\nVFLLS-FAHGO\nSUSPECT TAKEN\n\"RENO. March 2. The first arrest\nin connection with the robbery of\nseveral thousand dollars in gold and\nsilver from one of the Wells-Fargo\nexpress wagons iu Reno, February\n17th, was' made at Oolconda yester-\n'day afternoon, arid the arrest will\nprobably prove the first real clue the\nWells-Fargo detectives will have to\nwork on.\nConstable Johnson of Golconda ar\nrested a man at Golconda, who was\na total stranger there and in the su\nrounding country, who was about\nhalf intoxicated and was talking\nwildly and freely about how \"he had\ngot the best of at least one great\ncorporation,\" and that he knew who\nit was who had committed the bold\ntheft.\nThe man was well dressed, his\nclothes apparently being quite new,\nand he was; spending money with\n-great abandon, and would frequently\nsay \"that he had lots more where\n'that came from.\"\"\nWhen taken into custody by Con\nstable Johnson, the man quieted\ndown and would have lirtle to say.\nHe would not divulge' his name. Bas\ning that \"John .Tones\" would be suf\nficient for the purpose.\nWhen asked where his money\ncame from, he said that, \"he had re\ncently gotten a great deal of money\nfrom the Wells-Fargo Express Com\npany,\" but immediately afterwards\nseemed sorry that he had said any\nthing at all. and could not he in\nduced to add to the statement.\nITALIAN RACERS\nENTER PROTEST\nCHICAGO, Match i. itefore lear-\ning fhlcago today the drivers of the\nItalian car tiled n foinml protest\nuRiiinM the American car. This doc\nument recites that the AinerlrHn ma\nehine was altered while it was tin\nd-rvolng repair at itiiflalo; that It\nim -towed two cU) without the\nmotor running; that it was towed b\na I roll.. v car lu Indiana; tli.it It used\nili mill ond tin lu-tween Mirhlaaii\nI'i'y, hid., and Chicago, and that it\nt put on sIcdscH.\nTry our four year olii j,(1it and\ni.rry nines M 13 t Ballon. II.\n.1. tun Co. tr\nMbcrlbc for The Boaaaia.\nLURED WOMEN\nTHEN BEAT THEM\nELY, Nev.. March 2. Dr. Geo.\nB. Simpson, prominent physician of\nthis city, is under arrest here on a\ncharge of beating Mrs. Truesdale and\nMiss Bertreby, two women employed\nn the Northern hotel.\nIt is alleged by the women that\nDr. Simpson got them into the base\nment of the Union drug store and\nbeat them severely and that he would\nhave murdered them had not an offi\ncer heard their cries and rushed to\ntheir rescue.\nMrs. Truesdale asserts that she\nwa\"s passing the drug store when she\nheard a woman screaming and that\non entering the basement of the store\nwhere the screams were heard she\nfound Dr. Simpson beating Miss Ber\ntreby. She further alleges that when\nhe saw her. Dr. Simpson turned upon\nher and also gave her a severe beating.\nThe physician claims that the wj-\nmen were fighting in his drug store\nand that he had to beat them to\nmake tern desist.\nThe physician is now out on $200\nbonds.\no\nForerunner of a Greater Prosperity.\nRENOITES BUY\nCALIFORNIA MINE\nAL'BURX, March 2. F. E. Brye,\nP. Lozano and A. X. Smith have\nbonded the Bellevue mine at Ophir\nto a company from Reno. The latter\nhave not as yet incorporated and\nhave not yet taken any title to desig\nnate the company. They took chargj\nof the mine Monday and proceeded at\nonce to sink and otherwise develop\nthe vein. The company has elected\nthe following officers: Richard Kir-\nman, president; \"YV. J. Harris, vica\npresident; Fred Grob. treasurer, and\nR. J. Trimble, manager.\nThese officials are 'connected with\nthe management of the Farmers and\nMerchants' Bank at Reno. Manager\nTrimble and his associate, J.' E. Gig-\nnaux, are Nevada mining experts and\nengineers. Captain W. C. Rose Df\nReno, also a mining man, negotiated\nthe deal and is a member of the com\npany. The company is strong financially\nand guided by its expert manager\nwill assuredly open a new era iii\nquartz mining in this county. The\nvein is rich, and has always paid lt3\nowners. The last crushing of thirty\ntons averaged $50 per ton.\nTURNING OUT\nTHE BEST WORK\nThe bindery of the Bonanza is\nturning out the best work in the\ncity, and it is giving such great satis\nfaction that anyone who has his work\ndone there once, never goes anywhere\nelse. The plant is the fln?st and\nmost complete, not only in the State,\nhut this side of San F'ranclsco. We\ncan turn out all kinds of work that\nis demanded in the offices of lawyers,\nbrokers, promoters, mining compan\nies, or for any other kind of business,\nand we guarantee satisfaction in\nevery respect. One trial will be sum-\ncient to cstnlillxh the truth of this\nstatement. It pays to go where only\nthe best kind of work Is done, aad\nIt pays to patronize horn Industry.\nKin lie slots of Khmr Hi ok. now\nbelna sold for benefit of creditors.\nSeo billows for price.\nJournals, cash book and ledgers\njust the thing th merchant needs\nbest thut can h made. For sale at\nthe ttounnta office.\n(Vvtlfli ate of location at this\noffice.\nWORKMEN KILLED\nBY AN EXPLOSION\n(By Assoicated Press. 1\nSPOKANE. Wash., March 2. Two\nmen were instantly killed by an ex\nplosion near Marcus, Wash., this\nmorning, two more are believed to\nbe dead, and another fatally injured.\nwhile several are suferlng from\nbruises, the result of a landslide.\nwreckitiK crew was put ling in a blast\nto clear the track and a stick of dy\nnamite had been placed In one of the\nholes, when an Italian began to tamo\nIt with his drill, musing it to ex\nplodi'.\nSMOOTH FORGER\nIS IN THE TOILS\n(My Aamoi luted Pits.\nI.Orf ANGKI.KS. March 2. Chus.\nVltetnii, hu lil to he known In evei\ni In of iiiiHn inni't In California hy\ndifferent alluM-n. wti micnied here\nthis afternoon on a i liaise of liiivlni:\nnie a dixit sn i ..lie. i hut nni It\nI'll nA. The paper ptirixM led Ioi hII\nf..l l.'iluo t U slftte.l thai Vltein.l\na tin in. rlv ahler of n small hum:\nIn Wi'illprr, Xebruaka.\nHART DISTRICT\nIS LOOKING GOOD\n\"If Hart were in Nevada it would\nbe having as big a boom as Raw\nhide,\" said Walter C. Stone, upon his\nreturn from an automobile trip to the\nnew camp across the line. He was\naccompanied by E. R. Thompson. Mr.\nStono continued:\n\"Mr. Thompson' and myself have\nnot yet acquired any holdings in the\ncamp, but we have two men there\nwho are lining up several proposi\ntions for us.\n\"I think a great deal of the new\ndistrict, from a prospective stand\npoint. The first glimpse is not re\nassuring, for the entire country rock\nis granite, but in the immediate vi\ncinity of the new camp there is a\ngreat intrusion of porphyry, in which\nand along the lines of contact the\nvalues are found. 1\n\"The croppings are bold and the\nledges seem to be of enormous size\nand to possess permanency. While\nsrjme high grade is being taken out,\nit Is only by sorting and I think that\nthe future of the diggings is a large\nmilling proposition.\n\"You would be astonished to find\nthe cheapness of things there, for it\nto be a desert country. Why, for\n$7.50 a ton ore can be transported to\nNeedles and treated in the smelter\nthere. It is only a three-mile haul\nto the nearest point on the railroad.\n\"The formation at Hart is very\nsimilar to that at Searchlight. The\ntwo places are not more than fifteen\nmiles apart on an airline. Hart will\nundoubtedly become as Important a\ntown as Searchlight, and possibly\ngreater, if It ever gets mills of lis\nown. There will be no difficulty In\ndeveloping water and supplies can be\nhauled In over a branch railroad.\n\"Hart is very different from a\nNevada mining camp. There Is only\none saloon for 500 men and no gamb\nling whatever. Vhere Is nothing of\nthe boom and hurrah which attaches\nItself to a new mining camp on this\nsldo of the State line.\" Goldfleld\nNews.\nTonopah Light and Power Co.\nReduction In Price of Lamps\n16-8-4-2 candle power Lump .20\n50 watt Meridian, 25 candle power,\n100 watt Meridian, 50 candle power,\n250 watt Radiator\n500 watt Radiator\nSPKCIAL LAMPS IX 1M50I0RTI0X.\nHewiire of old refilled lamps that are on the market.\n,45\n,65\n,00\n25\nlVVl:ll KWIVM.KK.\nCHICAGO, March 2. John Stl\nP-n. a disbarred ChlcHHo lawyer, whi\nwith several tiHsnelnte wn IndirleJ\nseveral months neo on a chnriie of\nhuvliiK nwd the mail to defraud pro\nmoters of business entci pi Ihcx, wm\ncon h ied Ionia lit In the Federal\nCourt.\nM.I II .ill Pile Ceinetlv, pi lev .\"lOc. I-\nBunrapieed. I'm up remlv to use.\ntine H'iplli Hllou prompt relief in n\nform of piles SiMtlhes Mini liesl.4\nHold bv Tonopah Drug Co\nCertificates of (oration at (his\noffice.\nTHE TONOPAH BANKING CORPORATION\nCapital and Surplus Fully Paid $375,000.00\nA enteral Banking Baalnesn transacted. Excaaaze BouKht and Sold\nall the Prlav